                  <bindingDesc resp="#BCBB">
                     <binding notAfter="1425" notBefore="1400">
                        <p>15th century, early, <placeName key="place_1000080">Italian</placeName> (contemporary with manuscript): wood boards; <ref target="https://digital.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/objects/d53ebcf1-e706-402f-85e5-bc18604d630e/">brown leather, tooled on each cover </ref>
                           with blind lines and stamps in near-ropework frames, around a decorative gilt centrepiece built up with a repeated concave-lozenge stamp; spine cross-hatched 
                           with blind double lines, no title; traces of two strap-and-pin fastenings with leather straps running from fore-edge of front board to large pins near 
                           centre of back, all lost; edges plain. Spine repaired, 20th century, Bodleian. If the gilt is original, then this is the earliest known example of
                              European gold-tooling, and would likely be the result of Islamic influence (though in all other respects it is very unlike Islamic gilt
                              work)</p>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
